Bombadier Dash 8 Series 100 previously know as de Havilland Canada Dash 8

While boasting impressive technology for the time, they had some very serious issues.  the rotary drum computer was unreliable and often failed completely rendering the radar system useless.  The aircraft itself was highly vulnerable to corrosion which is a serious oversight for a carrier based aircraft.  49 of the original 59 airframes were updated to E-2B spec in 1971.
Notes text: given the problems, corrosion among them and the aircraft having been around for 7 years, i am assuing the other 10 aircraft that were not uprated were simply scrappe

Description text: Far more successful than the E-2A, this version actually had a service life of meaningful duration.
Notes text: many of the early E-2B's were really E-2A's with upgraded sensors, computers, and a solution to the corrosion problem they faced.

Description text: the 'Basic Charlie'.  This verson introduced several significant upgrades to the E-2B, and is regarded as the first truly successful model of the hawkeye.  It brings the APS-125 and ALQ-59, allowing for the first time passive fleet surveilance.
Notes text: should add group 1 and group 2 versions

Description text: these feature slightly uprated engines, and new 8 bladed props allowing for slight improvements in speed, as well as a slight fuel capacity increase allowing for slightly better range.

Group Zero is the result of continuous gradual upgrades to the 'basic charlies'.  by this stage of things they are using the APS-139 and a much more accurate ALR-73 ESM, and a number of other less simulatable changes.

Group 1 was rather underwhelming, and not only was it short lived but produced in small numbers.  It brings the APS-139, and improvements to crew electronics, such as a more difficult to jam radio system.

A 'nothing less than fantastic' upgrade of the E-2C's.  This version introduces the APS-145 radar, improved IFF, new workstations that eliminates the old radar scopes with color NTDS displays, a 3 channel link 16, and TAMPS mission planning and recording system.
